e native may fail? The rule permits catching unsupported dynamic class loader errors, but I wonder about Groovy initialization failures. To effectively cover dynamic access, we might need to invoke it. If I remove the `LinkageError` catch, will that lead to missing tests? I have to ensure the tests don’t silently pass, especially if the resolver didn’t execute in JVM.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Examining error handling in tests**\\n\\nI'm considering if I should only catch errors in the public API test rather than the resolver. Native might face a `NoClassDefFound` error due to a static initializer for closures, but linking errors are generally accepted. I wonder if I could ensure the class body executes without the original closure using Unsafe, but that seems tricky. Would invoking a method handle be a good alternative? If Groovy initialization fails on the JVM, could that explain the lack of coverage? I think direct helper calls should resolve the issue.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_QXowWj61xyLb9TPn7mdf7w9i|fc_00c9c94b8643caf7016a019d83cb448194b14455a41aee2ced", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "git diff -- tests/src/io.rest-assured/rest-assured/5.5.0/build.gradle tests/src/io.rest-assured/rest-assured/5.5.0/src/test/java/io_rest_assured/rest_assured/RestAssuredHttpBuilderGroovyHelperInner_flattenToString_closure1Test.java tests/src/io.rest-assured/rest-assured/5.5.0/src/test/java/io/restassured/internal/RestAssuredHttpBuilderGroovyHelperFlattenToStringClosure1Access.java | sed -n '1,240p'"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 995, "output": 1016, "cacheRead": 67584, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 69595, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1778490733900, "responseId": "resp_00c9c94b8643caf7016a019d6e9ef48194bd06dfa09e586e79"}, "toolResults": [{"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_QXowWj61x